[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] In computing, an **error code** (or a **return code**) is a numeric or alphanumeric code that indicates the nature of an error and, when possible, why it occurred.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Error codes can be reported to end users of software, returned from communication protocols, or used within programs as a method of representing anomalous conditions.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Error codes are commonly encountered on displays of consumer electronics to users in order to communicate or specify an error.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] They can also be indicated by lights or beeps, e.g., if a device does not have a display.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] They are commonly reported by consumer electronics when users bring electronics to perform tasks that they cannot do (e.g., dividing by zero), or when the program within a device encounters an anomalous condition.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Error codes reported by consumer electronics are used to help diagnose and repair technical problems.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] An error code can be communicated to relevant support staff to identify potential fixes, or can simplify research into the cause of an error.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] There is no definitive format for error codes, meaning that error codes typically differ from/between products and or companies.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Error codes in computers can be passed to the system itself, to judge how to respond to the error.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Often error codes come synonymous with an exit code or a return value.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] The system may also choose to pass the error code to its user(s).
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] The Blue screen of death is an example of how the Windows operating system communicates error codes to the user.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Error codes can be used within a computer program to represent an anomalous condition.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] A computer program can take different actions depending on the value of an error code.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Different programming languages, operating systems, and programming environments often have their own conventions and standards for the meanings and values of error codes.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] The usage of error codes as an error handling strategy is often contrasted against using exceptions for error handling.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Communication protocols typically define a standard set of error codes, as a means of communicating the status or result of an operation between the entities in the system.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Error codes in automobiles, sometimes referred to as trouble codes, indicate to a driver or car mechanic what is wrong with a vehicle before repairs are initiated.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] In vehicles with CAN buses, error codes are often five-digit codes that pinpoint a particular car fault.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/error-code] Car owners can make use of an on-board diagnostics scanner or an owner's manual to identify the meaning of a trouble code.
