[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] In computer science, **robustness** is the ability of a computer system to cope with errors during execution and cope with erroneous input.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Robustness can encompass many areas of computer science, such as robust programming, robust machine learning, and Robust Security Network.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Formal techniques, such as fuzz testing, are essential to showing robustness since this type of testing involves invalid or unexpected inputs.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Alternatively, deliberate fault injection can be used to test robustness.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Various commercial products perform robustness testing of software analysis.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] In general, building robust systems that encompass every point of possible failure is difficult because of the vast quantity of possible inputs and input combinations.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Since all inputs and input combinations would require too much time to test, developers cannot run through all cases exhaustively.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Instead, the developer will try to generalize such cases.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] For example, imagine inputting some integer values.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Some selected inputs might consist of a negative number, zero, and a positive number.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] When using these numbers to test software in this way, the developer generalizes the set of all reals into three numbers.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] This is a more efficient and manageable method, but more prone to failure.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Generalizing test cases is an example of just one technique to deal with failure—specifically, failure due to invalid user input.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Systems generally may also fail due to other reasons as well, such as disconnecting from a network.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Regardless, complex systems should still handle any errors encountered gracefully.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] There are many examples of such successful systems.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Some of the most robust systems are evolvable and can be easily adapted to new situations.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Programs and software are tools focused on a very specific task, and thus are not generalized and flexible.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] However, observations in systems such as the internet or biological systems demonstrate adaptation to their environments.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] One of the ways biological systems adapt to environments is through the use of redundancy.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Humans generally only need one kidney, but having a second kidney allows room for failure.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] This same principle may be taken to apply to software, but there are some challenges.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] When applying the principle of redundancy to computer science, blindly adding code is not suggested.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Blindly adding code introduces more errors, makes the system more complex, and renders it harder to understand.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Code that does not provide any reinforcement to the already existing code is unwanted.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] The new code must instead possess equivalent functionality, so that if a function is broken, another providing the same function can replace it, using manual or automated software diversity.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] To do so, the new code must know how and when to accommodate the failure point.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] This means more logic needs to be added to the system.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] But as a system adds more logic, components, and increases in size, it becomes more complex.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Thus, when making a more redundant system, the system also becomes more complex and developers must consider balancing redundancy with complexity.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Currently, computer science practices do not focus on building robust systems.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Rather, they tend to focus on scalability and efficiency.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] One of the main reasons why there is no focus on robustness today is because it is hard to do in a general way.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Robust programming is a style of programming that focuses on handling unexpected termination and unexpected actions.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] It requires code to handle these terminations and actions gracefully by displaying accurate and unambiguous error messages.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] These error messages allow the user to more easily debug the program.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] When building software, the programmer assumes users are out to break their code.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] The programmer also assumes that their own written code may fail or work incorrectly.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] The programmer assumes users will try incorrect, bogus and malformed inputs.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] As a consequence, the programmer returns to the user an unambiguous, intuitive error message that does not require looking up error codes.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] The error message should try to be as accurate as possible without being misleading to the user, so that the problem can be fixed with ease.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] This information should be hidden from the user so that the user does not accidentally modify them and introduce a bug in the code.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] are correctly built, users use them without finding loopholes to modify the interface.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] The interface should already be correctly implemented, so the user does not need to make modifications.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] The user therefore focuses solely on their own code.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Very often, code is modified and may introduce a possibility that an "impossible" case occurs.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Impossible cases are therefore assumed to be highly unlikely instead.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] The developer thinks about how to handle the case that is highly unlikely, and implements the handling accordingly.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Robust machine learning typically refers to the robustness of machine learning algorithms.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] For a machine learning algorithm to be considered robust, either the testing error has to be consistent with the training error, or the performance is stable after adding some noise to the dataset.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Recently, consistently with their rise in popularity, there has been an increasing interest in the robustness of neural networks.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] This is particularly due their vulnerability to adversarial attacks.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] Robust network design is the study of network design in the face of variable or uncertain demands.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] In a sense, robustness in network design is broad just like robustness in software design because of the vast possibilities of changes or inputs.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/robustness-computer-science] There exist algorithms that tolerate errors in the input.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
