[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] In computing, a **stack trace** (also called **stack backtrace** or **stack traceback**) is a report of the active stack frames at a certain point in time during the execution of a program.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] When a program is run, memory is often dynamically allocated in two places: the stack and the heap.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Memory is continuously allocated on a stack but not on a heap.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Stack also refers to a programming construct, thus to differentiate it, this stack is referred to as the program's **function call stack**.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Technically, once a block of memory has been allocated on the stack, it cannot be easily removed as there can be other blocks of memory that were allocated after it.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Each time a function is called in a program, a block of memory called an **activation record** is allocated on top of the call stack.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Generally, the activation record stores the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] What exactly it contains and how it's laid out is determined by the calling convention.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Programmers commonly use stack tracing during interactive and post-mortem debugging.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] End-users may see a stack trace displayed as part of an error message, which the user can then report to a programmer.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] A stack trace allows tracking the sequence of nested functions called - up to the point where the stack trace is generated.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] In a post-mortem scenario this extends up to the function where the failure occurred (but was not necessarily caused).
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Sibling calls do not appear in a stack trace.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Many programming languages, including Java and C#, have built-in support for retrieving the current stack trace via system calls.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Before `std::stacktrace` was added in standard library as a container for `std::stacktrace_entry`, pre-C++23 has no built-in support for doing this, but C++ users can retrieve stack traces with (for example) the stacktrace library.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] In JavaScript, exceptions hold a `stack` property that contain the stack from the place where it was thrown.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] As an example, the following Python program contains an error.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Running the program under the standard Python interpreter produces the following error message.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] The stack trace shows where the error occurs, namely in the `c` function.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] It also shows that the `c` function was called by `b`, which was called by `a`, which was in turn called by the code on line 16 (the last line) of the program.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] The activation records for each of these three functions would be arranged in a stack such that the `a` function would occupy the bottom of the stack and the `c` function would occupy the top of the stack.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] The exception lists functions in descending order, so the most-inner call is first.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Java also allows retrieving the current stack trace using `java.lang.Thread::getStackTrace()`, or displaying the stack trace at an error using `java.lang.Throwable::printStackTrace()`.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] A stack trace in Java is represented as `java.lang.StackTraceElement[]`, an array.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] C does not have native support for obtaining stack traces, but libraries such as glibc provide this functionality.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] In C and C++, some compiler optimizations may interfere with the call stack information that can be recovered at runtime.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] For instance, inlining can cause missing stack frames, tail call optimizations can replace one stack frame with another, and frame pointer elimination can prevent call stack analysis tools from correctly interpreting the contents of the call stack.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] For example, glibc's `backtrace()` function returns an output with the program function and memory address.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Prior to C++23, no mechanisms in C++ existed to obtain stack traces, but third-party libraries like *Boost.Stacktrace* offered stack traces.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] C# offers a `System.Diagnostics.StackTrace` class.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Functions that use the panic macro are "unrecoverable" and the current thread will become poisoned experiencing stack unwinding.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Functions that return a `std::result::Result` are "recoverable" and can be handled gracefully.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] However, recoverable errors cannot generate a stack trace as they are manually added and not a result of a runtime error.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] As of June 2021, Rust has experimental support for stack traces on unrecoverable errors.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] Rust supports printing to stderr when a thread panics, but it must be enabled by setting the `RUST_BACKTRACE` environment variable.
[src:anyhow-error-rust/stack-trace] When enabled, such backtraces look similar to below, with the most recent call first.
